profile_positions.description:
South Sudan, Juba, Mott MacDonald. Senior positions as 
•	team leader of the Basic Services Fund (£100m with DFID as lead donor), with an integrated support package for primary schools, WASH and primary health clinics, including six hundred primary schools with training for PTAs, 1500 teachers with teacher training, five hundred boreholes & six thousand latrines (for schools, primary health clinics and communities),
•	deputy and acting team leader of Girls Education South Sudan (£30m), and 
•	Mott MacDonald Project office operational manager. 

Main responsibilities included assisting in and supervising : 

1.	Design and operate grantee selection namely national and int. NGOs to implement interventions financed by the programs;
2.	Design and operate M&E database for information on efficiency and effectiveness of the NGO projects for construction, training and capacity building; assist in maximizing female participation in all project activities;
3.	Financial management of NGO grants: Disburse funds to the NGO projects, ensure auditing of accounts, fiduciary arrangements and up to date financial reporting of grant receiving organisations; Report on NGO disbursements and do financial periodic forecasts;
4.	Operate secretariat of the projects’ Steering Committees;
5.	Donor coordination;
6.	Project periodic progress reporting in inception-, annual- ,quarterly progress and completion reports;
7.	Security, logistics and compound management.

PRASAC (Programme de Rehabilitation et d’Appui au Secteur Agricole du Cambodge) - a quick-impact intervention to invest in repairs after decades of civil strife, financed by the EU (€40 m for the first phase of 5 years) and implemented in six provinces ( implemented by EuroConsult in the two provinces of Kampong Cham and Kampong Chnang) with components in community development, credit, foodsecurity (irrigation, rice-seed production and agricultural extension), and domestic water supply. As zonal manager/agronomist responsibilities in the province of Kampong Chaam included training and Institutional development in particular:
1. initialize and oversee the recruitment of the team of two hundred national project staff and lead the team in the implementation of the work plans;
2. PRA survey of needs and constraints assessment of target groups (150 villages; 10,000 persons);
set-up, implement and develop rice-seed multiplication program as an integrated part of  the agricultural extension service;
3. initialize and complete the process of institutionalization of each project component in its respective local structure (Credit Associations, Village Development Committees, Water User Associations, Drinking Water Committees) and introduce cost recovery;
4. initialize and complete the process of institutionalization of each project component in its respective local government department;
5. set-up and oversee implementation of post-flood actions  after Mekong river floods (emergency rice-seed distribution, domestic water supply);
6.prepare all work plans, budgets, monitor & supervise implementation, and progress reporting; 
7. pro-active co-ordination with all other donors and projects (Ausaid, IRRI, FAO, WFP, EU-ECHO, World bank and NGOs);
8.design and implement bench-mark surveys for monitoring impact on the effects of the quality rice seed, credit and irrigation interventions.

Bangladesh: agronomist with the Crop Diversification Program of the Ministry of Agriculture and co-financed by  the Dutch and Canadian governments.  Responsibilities included the promotion, training, M&E  of non-rice crops, in particular:
1.	formal and informal surveys to select for participation decentralized organizations, mostly     NGOs, as partners in  a nation-wide crop diversification promotion campaign;
2.	promote the participation of female members of the rural households in the crop diversification extension, training, credit and input supply;
3.	identify critical elements (storage, seed) in primary production value-chain to address for successful crop diversification;
4.	increase revenues from crop diversification by training in production, storage and processing of seeds;
5.	promote the use of quality inputs into crop production with the double aim to alleviate environmental pressure and stabilize revenues (risk reduction);
6.	In recurrent post-flood periods address issues of decentralized agricultural input distribution.
